As seen from above, most red wine samples received the moderate quality rating of either 5 and 6. This also reflects in the median and mean quality score of 6 and 5.636, respectively.

No wines was given the lowest and highest possible score of 0 and 10. Scores given range from 3 to 8, with very few wines obtained the rating of either 3 or 8.

Next, we are going to look at the distribution of fixed acidity in all wine samples.

It appears that most wines contain 5 to 14 g/dm^3 of fixed acidity, with the median and mean amount being 7.90 and 8.32 g/dm^3 respectively.

We can see that there’s almost a fixed range in the amount of chlorides contained in wine samples, from about 0.06 to slightly more than 0.1 g/dm^3. It is uncommon to see chlorides exceeding 0.114 g/dm^3, although there are two outliers at 0.61 g/dm^3. And unlike citric acid which we explored earlier, chlorides is an indispensable ingredient since its amount is more than zero in all wine samples in our dataset.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

The dataset contains 1599 red wines with the following 12 attributes: - fixed acidity. - volatile acidity. - citric acid. - residual sugar. - chlorides. - free sulfur dioxide. - total sulfur dioxide. - density. - pH. - sulphates. - alcohol. - quality.

Quality is a discrete quantitative variable ( 0 is the lowest and 10 is the highest ), while all other variables as listed above are continuous quantitative.

Some obversations:

  • Most red wines receive the quality score of either 5 or 6, with the lowest and highest score in the dataset being 3 and 8 respectively.
  • Residual sugar, fixed acidity, chlorides, total sulfur dioxide and sulphates data are skewed to the right.
  • pH values in the dataset are normally distributed, with the vast majority being between 2.8 and 3.75.
  • All density values are very close to exactly 1.
  • Most alcohol contents are from 8.4 to 14 percent.
  • Not all wines contain citric acid.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main features in this dataset are quality and alcohol.

We shall be investigating further to see if there is any correlation between alcohol and the quality rating of red wine.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

Volatile acidity, sulphates are some of the other variables that we will pay particular attention to in our analysis to see whether they also influence the quality of wine and if so, to what extent.

Other noteworthy relations include:

  • citric acid and fixed acidity.

  • density and fixed acidity.

  • pH and fixed acidity.

  • citric acid and volatile acidity.

  • citric acid and pH.

  • free sulfur dioxide and total sulfur dioxide.

  • alcohol and density.

We will explore all these relations as we go further into this section. But first, Let’s create scatterplot matrices of all variables in our dataset:

We can see that there’s a pretty strong positive correlation of 0.6717 between fixed acidity and citric acid amount in our wine dataset.

This makes sense since citric acid is a fixed acidity itself, and if citric acid increases/decreases by a certain amount, that same fluctuation should also apply to fixed acidity.

Contrary to the above, the relationship between fixed acidity and pH appears to be negatively correlated at -0.6830.

Looking back at the description of pH, we know that the more acidic a wine is, the lower pH score it will receive.

So our finding just reinforces our intuition that there should be a negative correlation between these 2 variables.

We noticed that there is a moderate negative correlation between red wine’s volatile acidity and quality score.

A moderate positive correlation also exists between alcohol amount and a red wine’s quality score.

By continuing to explore further, we found out that with some minor exception, as quality score increases, the mean amount of alcohol and sulphates in wine samples of each score also increases. The reverse is true with volatile acidity, for its average value decreases as quality score improves.

The same trend can also be observed with all quartile values, including the median. To be more specific, for alcohol and sulphates, all quartiles values generally increases as quality rating goes up. Volatile acidity, on the other hand, displayed a downward trend as quality improves.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features
(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

Beside the relationship between quality score and some noteworthy variables, we found out there exists some significant correlation between other features in our red wine dataset.

Citric acid and fixed acidity, density and fixed acidity, free sulfur dioxide and total sulfur dioxide, all these pairs of features show moderate positive correlation.

Fixed acidity and pH, on the other hand, display moderate negative correlation to each other. This moderate negative correlation is also true with citric acid and pH, citric acid and volatile acidity, alcohol and density as shown above in the plots.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The strongest relationships are those between citric and fixed acidity, density and fixed acidity, pH and fixed acidity, free sulfur dioxide and total sulfur dioxide, with correlation value being close to -0.7 or 0.7.

With that being said, none of the feature pairs in the red wine dataset could be said to strongly correlate with one another ( with strong correlation assumed to be equal or larger than 0.7, or, equal or lower than -0.7).

Multivariate Plots Section

In this section, we are going to dive even deeper into the red wine dataset by examining the relationships between multiple features at the same time.

For example, previously we have studied the correlation between alcohol and density. Now, we are going to take a closer look at this relationship by adding another feature: quality score.

Besides, we will create density plots for a number of features by dividing them into subgroups based on their quality scores.

The above density plot of volatile acidity reveals that wines with higher quality score such as 6 or 8 tend to have lower volatile acidity amount, typically below 0.8 g/dm^3. Meanwhile, those with volatile acidity amount more than 0.8 g/dm^3 are much more likely to receive lower quality score of 3 or 4.

Regarding alcohol, it is evident that wines with lower quality score tend to be skewed to the right, or they are more likely to have less alcohol percentage, 12 % or below. For wines with more than 12 % of alcohol, it is more common to receive a better quality score like 7 or 8.

Here we have a scatterplot of alcohol vs density, classified into subgroups based on quality score. It appears that wines with lower quality score of 3, 4 and 5 have lower alcohol percentage and a more limited range of density values. For wines with high quality score of 7 and above, they often have an alcohol percentage of more than 12 % ( similar to our earlier findings) and a wider range of density values.

Most wines, regardless of quality score, have a chlorides amount of below 0.2. However, it appears as chlorides amount increases beyond 0.2, a low quality score of 3 is also much more common.

We can easily see that as quality score increases, the lines that correspond with each quality score also shift to the right. This implies that a higher amount of sulphates will lead to an increasing chance of improvement in quality.

As the amount of fixed acidity increases, the higher quality score of at least 7 also appears more frequently. In addition, we can see that for wines with density below 0.995 g/cm^3, they are predominantly receive the quality score of 6 and above.

As seen from the plot, wines with the quality score of 6 and above usually have pH approximately less than 3.3 and citric acid amount of more than 0.25 g/dm^3.

We can see that as volatile acidity amount increases, quality score also drops. This aligns with our previous findings. Furthermore, wines with quality score of 7 and 8 are more likely to contain a citric acid amount of more than 0.25 g/dm^3.

Multivariate Analysis

  • The density plots of alcohol, volatile acidity, chlorides and sulphates gave us a deeper understanding than what was presented in part 1 and 2 by creating multiple lines in the same plot based upon quality score. On the other hand, an increase in the amount of alcohol and sulphates leads to a greater probability of obtaining a higher quality score.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

  • From part 2, we have learnt there seems to be very weak correlation between chlorides and quality score a wine receives. However, in this section, it seems that when chlorides amount exceeds 0.1 g/dm^3, it is much more likely for the low quality score of 3 to appear. The fact that there are only a few wines with this much chlorides amount in the dataset means that this would not be reflected in the correlation value.

  • Wines with density of below 0.993 g/cm^3 receive very high quality score of 6 and above. Again since there are not too many wines with this feature, it is not until this section that this has finally been found out.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

Wines with lowest quality score of 3 in the dataset have the highest median volatile acidity amount, whereas those with highest quality score of 7 or 8 have the lowest median volatile acidity value. To put it another way, as quality score improves, the median volatile acidity amount also drops.

The same trend could also be seen for the third quartile and to a lesser extent, the first quartile values. Regarding the first quartile, its value decreases as quality score goes up until 8, where it appears to move up a little bit.

Plot Two

Description Two

Low quality scores such as 3 or 4 appear more often when the alcohol percentage is small, specifically below 12 percent. As the alcohol percentage increases, higher quality scores like 7 or 8 also occur more frequently.

In addition, low quality scores like 3, 4 or 5 typically reach their peaks when alcohol percentage is below 10 and begin to drop significantly after that, when they are slowly taken over by higher quality scores.

Plot Three

Description Three

The above scatter plot of fixed acidity by density and quality reveals that when density remains the same, it is very likely for wines with higher amount of fixed acidity to receive a better quality score like 7 or 8. ——
